## Test Smell Audit — `OrderProcessorTests.cs`

### 1. Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell count | Affected tests |
|----------|------------:|---------------:|
| High     | 4           | 4              |
| Medium   | 4           | 4              |
| Low      | 1           | (class-level)  |
| **Total**| **9**       | **8 methods**  |

---

### 2. Findings by Severity

#### 🔴 HIGH — Conditional Test Logic

**Test:** `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 24)

```csharp
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

**Problem:** The test doesn't know what it's asserting — one branch may never execute, giving false confidence.

**Fix:** Split into two deterministic tests with explicit Arrange sections:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_UnderThreshold_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-CHEAP", 1) } };
    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_OverThreshold_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-EXPENSIVE", 5) } };
    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

---

#### 🔴 HIGH — Assertion-Free Test

**Test:** `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)

```csharp
processor.ProcessOrder(order);
// nothing asserted
```

**Problem:** This only proves no exception is thrown — it verifies no behavior and will pass even if the implementation is gutted.

**Fix:** Assert observable side-effects:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_ValidOrder_PersistsAndNotifies()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    processor.ProcessOrder(order);

    Assert.IsTrue(_db.ContainsOrder(order.Id));
    Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasConfirmationSent(order.Id));
}
```

---

#### 🔴 HIGH — Sleepy Test

**Test:** `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 91)

```csharp
processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
Thread.Sleep(2000);
Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
```

**Problem:** Arbitrary sleep makes the test slow and flaky — CI load changes can cause intermittent failures.

**Fix:** Use `async/await` or a deterministic signal:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    await processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);

    Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
}
```

---

#### 🔴 HIGH — Mystery Guest

**Test:** `ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly` (line 139)

```csharp
